Free Meal Availability and Food Pantry Information.

Please be advised, through a partnership with the Windham Community Food Pantry at the Hope Restoration Church, WAJ will be providing "Grab and Go" free bagged meals for distribution to eligible WAJ students at their 117 Route 296 Windham location during the following hours of operation: Tuesday from 10:00 AM -12 Noon, Thursday from 10:00 AM - 12 Noon and Saturday 9:00 AM-12 Noon.

You may also access the WAJ website for further information at www.wajcs.org

post_text: Congratulations to Joe Lane and Brian VanValin on qualifying to Vex Robotics Tower Takeover State Championships in Syracuse. After going through 10 qualification rounds, they qualified 11th out of 35 teams. Their robot did well but got knocked out in the quarter finals. They've had a great run the last few years. Be proud of your accomplishments! It was a pleasure watching your passion for robotics come alive and work together as a team. You've made us all proud! #wajproud #wajnation #wajrobotics #6527A #vexrobotics @ Syracuse, New York

post_text:
WAJ is excited to be hosting an expo for parents of middle and high school students at this year’s Open House. Join us on September 26th from 6-7:30 in the WAJ gymnasium to meet your child’s teachers, coaches, and advisors. The evening will be full of valuable information about curriculum, homework, sports, clubs, technology and much more!

Elementary students can bring their parents along on a fun scavenger hunt to meet their teachers and see our school. Don’t forget to stop at the treasure box and the Book Fair!

We hope to see you there!

post_text: Congratulations to all of the WAJ elementary students who participated in the Ronald McDonald House Read-a-thon this year. Our school raised $3,582.25 for the Albany Ronald McDonald House and received the Grand Prize for greatest participation rate! Each student that participated received a pass to the VIA aquarium and a ticket to a Tri City Valley Cats baseball game. If you would like additional tickets to the game for other family members, please contact Nicole Baldner at 734-3400 ext. 1160 or nbaldner@wajcs,org.

Next week is Red Ribbon Week at WAJ. Red Ribbon Week is a national alcohol, tobacco and other drug and violence prevention awareness campaign. We will be observing the campaign by dressing up daily. Below is the schedule for the dress up days. Have fun!

Monday, October 22nd—Wear Red for Red Ribbon Week

Tuesday, October 23rd— Life is a Journey – Travel Drug Free (wear a shirt that shows where you have traveled or would like to travel)

Wednesday, October 24th— Unity Day! (wear orange)

Thursday, October 25th— Sock it to Drugs (wear your craziest socks)

Friday, October 26th – Friends Don’t Let Friends Use Drugs – (dress just like your friend)

Welcome back to a new school year, WAJ!

Here is a list of some fun upcoming events this week:

Tuesday, September 11th, 5:00 p.m.--Mandatory parent CROP meeting in the WAJ cafetorium. If you would like your child/children enrolled in the CROP program you must attend this event. Please contact Bernie Gribbons for any questions.

Wednesday, September 12th, 6:00 p.m.--New York State Trooper Craig Vedder, who presented to parents, students, and staff last year, will be giving a presentation on trends in Social Media. All parents are welcome to attend. The presentation will be followed by a PTA meeting.

Friday, September 14th, from 5:00 p.m. to 7:00 p.m.--WAJ's "Back to School Barbeque," which will be taking place in the front of the school. All are welcome to attend this wonderful event.

We hope to see anyone interested at these events!! Have a wonderful week!

post_text: Throughout the month of March, elementary students at WAJ will participate in the Ronald McDonald House Readathon. The Albany Ronald McDonald House provides free housing, meals and support to families with children being treated at hospitals in Albany. Several WAJ families have benefited from the RMH and now is our chance to give back. The students have all received their packets. Parents, please track the minutes your child reads each night on the calendar provided. In addition, please help your child ask family members, neighbors and friends if they would like to sponsor your child for reading. They can donate per minute read or make a flat donation. They can also donate online using the website provided in your packet. 100% of the donations go directly to the Albany RMH. All reading logs, sponsor forms and money should be returned to Mrs. Baldner in the envelope provided by April 3rd. Please contact Mrs. Baldner at 734-3400 ext. 1160 or nbaldner@wajcs.org. with any questions. Thank you for your support!

post_text:
Zones of Regulation at WAJ

At the February 9th Morning Program, a new program called Zones of Regulation was introduced to students by Mrs. Baldner, school counselor. Zones of Regulation teaches self-regulation by categorizing all the different ways we feel into four concrete colored zones. The Zones framework provides strategies to teach students to become more aware of and independent in controlling their emotions and impulses and improve their ability to problem solve conflicts. Mrs. Mattice’s 4th graders have been learning about the Zones all year and played a game of “Feelings Charades” with the other students at Morning Program, role playing some common feelings. In the future, more discussions about the Zones and tools for managing feelings will be explored with students at Morning Program and in the classrooms. To learn more about the Zones of Regulation, please visit www.zonesofregulation.com.

WAJ has begun a new program called Warrior of the Month to recognize students with good character and resiliency.

The elementary student chosen for November is Edwin Lopez! Edwin's teachers describe him as conscientious, respectful, kind to peers, responsible and he has a great positive attitude!

The 7-12 winners are Colin McCullar and Madeline Forbes! Madeline's teachers describe her as responsible, honest, diligent, hard working, determined, focused and kind.
Colin's teachers describe him as caring, helpful in class, considerate of others, a good friend to all and kind-hearted.

Congratulations Edwin, Madeline and Colin! Keep up the great work.

post_text: Some more pics from the WAJ Music Department trip to Cleveland!
text: Some more pics from the WAJ Music Department trip to Cleveland!

post_text: The WAJ Music Department just returned from their amazing adventure to Cleveland, OH where they had the opportunity to explore the Rock & Roll Hall of Fame followed by choral & small ensemble performances on their Main Stage. Later that afternoon the Band played the National Anthem at Progressive Stadium for a Cleveland Indians vs. Kansas City Royals game. Before heading home, the Bands and Choruses took to the stage at Cedar Point in Sandusky, OH for one final performance before spending some time enjoying all that the amusement park had to offer. Thank you to everyone who has shown their support through this process. It truly was an experience that none of us will soon forget!

post_text: Students in Ms. Larsen's 3rd grade class having fun with the new WAJ robots Alice and Oscar. Today students determined the length of one floor tile in centimeters, inches, and feet. They used this information to calculate the total length that the robot would travel. Students then used code to program the robot and to see if the robot could successfully travel the length of the line. The final hypothesis that the students made was that speed is a variable that changes the distance that the robot travels. Nice work 3rd grade!

ATTENTION INCOMING KINDERGARTEN FAMILIES:
Monday, May 15th – Visitation and Parent Orientation

Incoming kindergarten students will visit their classes from 9-10 AM followed by a short bus ride. While the students are visiting their future classrooms, their parents will receive a short tour of the building and will meet with an administrator, Mrs. Baldner, a nurse, Mrs. Mead and Mrs. Oftedal in the library where they will be provided with basic information about the assessment and registration process and will have an opportunity to ask questions.

Thursday, May 18th and Friday, May 19th – Registration and Assessment

We will hold the registration and assessment in the Learning Center at Windham Mountain. Mrs. Corrigan, Mrs. Coughlin, Mrs. Baldner, Mrs. Guy, Mrs. Peters and Mrs. Aplin will come to Windham Mountain both days to assist with the process.
